  "prompt": "What does IAS officers generally do after retirement?",
  "response": "After retirement, IAS (Indian Administrative Service) officers typically pursue various paths:\n\n1. Advisory Roles\n- Serving as consultants to government departments\n- Joining policy think tanks\n- Providing expert advice to organizations\n\n2. Academic Positions\n- Teaching in universities and management institutes\n- Writing research papers and books\n- Delivering lectures and guest sessions\n\n3. Public Service Roles\n- Joining government commissions\n- Serving as chairpersons of public sector undertakings\n- Working in regulatory bodies\n\n4. Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs)\n- Leading social welfare organizations\n- Working on developmental projects\n- Engaging in social entrepreneurship\n\n5. Corporate Sector\n- Taking board positions in private companies\n- Serving as corporate advisors\n- Consulting for multinational corporations\n\n6. Writing and Media\n- Authoring books on administration and governance\n- Writing columns for newspapers and magazines\n- Participating in media discussions\n\n7. Political Roles\n- Joining political parties\n- Contesting elections\n- Serving as advisors to political leaders\n\n8. Arbitration and Mediation\n- Working as arbitrators\n- Resolving legal disputes\n- Providing mediation services\n\n9. International Organizations\n- Working with UN agencies\n- Joining international development organizations\n\nThese options depend on individual interests, skills, and opportunities.",
